commits.message: Add .gitignore
Refactor gameState to eliminate unnecessary lambdas
Remove rows, cols, diagonals variables
Remove unused 'victory' function
Give piece a custom show method.  Remove an fmap call that turned pieces into strings.
Remove lambdas from boardRows / boardColumns

Merge pull request #1 from rcjara/master

Improvements from Raul.

comment.body: Many thanks! I think I've learnt a thing or too, but I'll have to look over it more than once for it to sink in. I particularly liked the use of concatMap and `map (zip range . repeat) range`.

issue.body:
b3881af  (19 hours)   <Raul Jara>      Add .gitignore 

Hopefully self explanatory.


    4a4ade8  (19 hours)   <Raul Jara>      Refactor gameState to eliminate unnecessary lambdas

    -    let rows = map (\l -> map (\s -> M.findWithDefault NoPiece s m) l) (boardRows board)
    -        columns = map (\l -> map (\s -> M.findWithDefault NoPiece s m) l) (boardColumns board)
    -        diagonals = map (\l -> map (\s -> M.findWithDefault NoPiece s m) l) (boardDiagonals board)
    +    let findPiece = flip (M.findWithDefault NoPiece) m
    +        rows      = map (map findPiece) $ boardRows board
    +        columns   = map (map findPiece) $ boardColumns board
    +        diagonals = map (map findPiece) $ boardDiagonals board
             lines = rows ++ columns ++ diagonals
         in
    -      if any (\line -> (all (\x -> x == X) line) || (all (\x -> x == O) line)) lines
    +      if any (\line -> (all (== X) line) || (all (== O) line)) lines
           then Victory
    -      else if all (\x -> x /= NoPiece) (concat rows)
    +      else if all (/= NoPiece) (concat rows)
                then Tie
                else Continue

We discussed these changes yesterday.

    2cb13ce  (18 hours)   <Raul Jara>      Remove rows, cols, diagonals variables

         let findPiece = flip (M.findWithDefault NoPiece) m
    -        rows      = map (map findPiece) $ boardRows board
    -        columns   = map (map findPiece) $ boardColumns board
    -        diagonals = map (map findPiece) $ boardDiagonals board
    -        lines = rows ++ columns ++ diagonals
    +        lineCoords = concatMap (\f -> f board) [boardRows, boardColumns, boardDiagonals]
    +        lines = map (map findPiece) lineCoords
         in
           if any (\line -> (all (== X) line) || (all (== O) line)) lines
           then Victory
    -      else if all (/= NoPiece) (concat rows)
    -           then Tie
    -           else Continue
    +      else if any (== NoPiece) (concat lines)
    +           then Continue
    +           else Tie

Here I wouldn't blame you if you felt I gave up clarity. I noticed the rows = / columns = / diagonals =  lines were all a bit reduntant, so I changed them to a map.  Then because I no longer had a rows variable I had to change the continue/tie checking.  I elected to optimize the continue case, short cutting the check if any NoPiece showed up.

    30d5161  (18 hours)   <Raul Jara>      Remove unused 'victory' function

    --- i.e. it only checks if the most recent move has ended the game
    -victory (Board size m) (row, column) piece =
    -    let row_coords = map (\y -> (row, y)) [1..size]
    -        col_coords = map (\x -> (x, column)) [1..size]
    -        squareEq p s = (M.findWithDefault NoPiece s m) == p
    -    in all (squareEq piece) row_coords || all (squareEq piece) col_coords
    
    This totally wasn't being used.
    
    3b0ffa6  (8 minutes)  <Raul Jara>      Give piece a custom show method.  Remove an fmap call that turned pieces into strings.
    -data Piece = X | O | NoPiece deriving (Eq, Show)
    +data Piece = X | O | NoPiece deriving (Eq)
    +
    +instance Show Piece where
    +  show X = "X"
    +  show O = "O"
    +  show _ = " "
    +
     showBoard :: Board -> String
    -showBoard (Board size m) = let lookup sq = M.findWithDefault " " sq (fmap show m)
    +showBoard (Board size m) = let lookup sq = show $ M.findWithDefault NoPiece sq m

We discussed this a little yesterday.

    62f9120  (8 minutes)  <Raul Jara>      (HEAD, fork/master, master) Remove lambdas from boardRows / boardColumns

      boardRows (Board size m) =
         let range = [1..size]
    -    in map (\r -> map (\c -> (r,c)) range) range
    +    in map (flip zip range . repeat) range
    
    
      boardColumns (Board size m) =
         let range = [1..size]
    -    in map (\c -> map (\r -> (r,c)) range) range
    +    in map (zip range . repeat) range


These functions are basically the same, and I noticed that the inner map (in both functions) was really just a zip, so I replaced it to that, and also got to make use of that function composition period.  Hooray!

commits.message: Use 'with' statement for opening file.
Print board if game is tied.
Removed hardcoded board size in `possible_moves`.

First version of minmax

`minmax` takes `board`, `player` (an Int) and optionally a function
`indmax` or `indmin`. Intermediate values are stored in a Dict of Dicts.

Currently the game is set up for Human vs. AI only.
Moved minmax functions to `minmax.jl`.
Corrected status code check for game end.
Renamed `minmax` to `minmax_with_cache`.
`move` now takes a tuple for the move position.
More informative variable names
min or max option passed as token
Both players can be human or computer AI

Caching now uses a (player, state) tuple

E.g. (1, :max) is stored separately to (1, :min).
Reverted `minmax_with_cache` to `minmax`.

Corrected `minmax` and simplified caching.

Using both `player` and `status` to decide on MIN or MAX was causing
problems with the algorithm. Player `1` should always be maximizing and
player `-1` should always be minimizing. This simplifies the caching,
and in addition the board state determines whose turn it is removing the
need for multiple dictionaries. The boards are now stored as strings to
avoid any potential mutibility problems.

Revert "try to improve the STDIN as IOStream workaround"

This reverts commit 4e8cabc337b4164b176534a85ffcfcd6578f947f.

Revert "make STDIN an IOStream on linux when the input stream is a file"

This reverts commit 64451781dcba91dc7a5b4884afdd5eb4153d9e41.

pull_request.title: Added `render_from_file`
pull_request.body:
Hi, I wrote some code for rendering templates directly from a file path. It stores the intermediate representation in a dictionary, so it doesn't need to load or parse the file more than once.

Let me know if you see any problems with this approach or if you think if shouldn't be included in the main library.

Thanks

Nick

commits.message:
Added `render_from_file`

Renders a template from `filepath` and `view`. It uses a Dict
`TEMPLATES` to store parsed templates, and if it has seen the
file before then it finds the compiled `MustacheTokens` in
`TEMPLATES` rather than calling `parse` a second time.

Docstrings added

color_print(), split_word(), tokenize() and atom()
Added check for LisSyntaxError in repl()
added 'cond' and tests
Added set! to language features.
Added 'begin' statement.

'env' now stores name, val pairs in lists

'env' previously contained (name, val) tuples, it now contains two
element lists, [name, val], as this allows the env to be mutated inside
a closure.

Quicksort implementation in Python

Tests 100 lists of random integers against the Python sorted() function.
removed move Pokemon exception handling
new test for incorrect closing parens
replaced Exception with LisSyntaxError

Fixed bug in parse_tokens()

This is a quick fix and I'm not sure if it fixes the parser entirely
but it now keeps track of the number of open parentheses and raises
a LisSyntaxError if an unexpected closing paren is found.
Updated README and removed debugging code
updated README and removed unused code
cleanup

pull_request.title: Added `render_from_file`
pull_request.body:
Hi, I wrote some code for rendering templates directly from a file path. It stores the intermediate representation in a dictionary, so it doesn't need to load or parse the file more than once.

Let me know if you see any problems with this approach or if you think if shouldn't be included in the main library.

Thanks

Nick

commits.message:
Added `render_from_file`

Renders a template from `filepath` and `view`. It uses a Dict
`TEMPLATES` to store parsed templates, and if it has seen the
file before then it finds the compiled `MustacheTokens` in
`TEMPLATES` rather than calling `parse` a second time.

Docstrings added

color_print(), split_word(), tokenize() and atom()
Added check for LisSyntaxError in repl()
added 'cond' and tests
Added set! to language features.
Added 'begin' statement.

'env' now stores name, val pairs in lists

'env' previously contained (name, val) tuples, it now contains two
element lists, [name, val], as this allows the env to be mutated inside
a closure.

Quicksort implementation in Python

Tests 100 lists of random integers against the Python sorted() function.
removed move Pokemon exception handling
new test for incorrect closing parens
replaced Exception with LisSyntaxError

Fixed bug in parse_tokens()

This is a quick fix and I'm not sure if it fixes the parser entirely
but it now keeps track of the number of open parentheses and raises
a LisSyntaxError if an unexpected closing paren is found.
Added color support (if termcolor is installed).

Simplified atom() function

Removed second try/except.
added new errors

Replaced Exception with IOError

The try/except for file IO now only catches an IOError.
Use LisNameError in lookup() and repl()

`match_route_handler`.

Changed argument name and type in `searchroute`.

Changed argument name from `route` to `parts` for consistency with
`match_route_handler` (where it is called) and indicated that it should
be an `Array`. Added description of the function with examples.

comment.body:
Hi Jeff, Stefan

Daniel and I have been looking over the differences between femtolisp and Biwa. It looks like they are reasonably compatible. We will need to include some of the functions from the SRFI1 list library (but the reference implementation is in Scheme anyway) that are used in the parser, and (as mentioned above) implement the string.find function.

The Biwa implementation on node.js only includes a little more than the browser version (IO and process), so we think it would be easier to test on this to start with. Do you have any idea of what kind of testing environment we would need to setup? Are there existing tests for the parser?

issue.body:
The Julia parser is written in Scheme and evaluated using Jeff's femtolisp implementation. It would be handy for many things, including the web repl to be able to parse Julia code in JavaScript. A couple of possible approaches exist:

1. Find a JavaScript Scheme implementation and port the existing flisp code to it.
2. Use [emscripten](https://github.com/kripken/emscripten) to compile flisp to JavaScript.

Not sure which approach is better, but this would be an interesting and largely self-contained project. See discussion here: https://groups.google.com/d/topic/julia-dev/SWkJWxrS5xo/discussion.
issue.title: port Julia parser to JavaScript
